in-bottom:0px;">Hi, and welcome back to Line Sheet. <strong>Sarah</strong>
=E2=80=9C<a href=3D"mailto:sshapiro@puck.news?utm_campaign=3DLine+Sheet+-+S=
UBSCRIBERS+%282%2F25%2F25%29&amp;utm_content=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%28=
2%2F25%2F25%29&amp;utm_medium=3Demail_action&amp;utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&a=
mp;utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a" style=3D"text-decoration:underline;color:=
#d40000;">SShapiro@puck.news</a>=E2=80=9D <strong>Shapiro </strong>is back =
today with some chatter from the C.P.G. world, an update from the affiliate=
-marketing trenches, and a dispatch from your local, perfectly manicured ou=
tdoor shopping center, where there is almost <em>undoubtedly</em> a Madewel=
l.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"=
margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">What happened to Madewell,
anyway? It was once the kinda-cool alternative to J.Crew. But instead of co=
ntinuing to chase the youth, it aged up with Millennial women, who are now =
moms hanging out at=E2=80=A6 outdoor shopping centers. The problem for Made=
well is that those shoppers have more choices now.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;=
">As you know, I=E2=80=99m in Europe this week. I=E2=80=99ll be back tomorr=
ow with an update on the layoffs at Saks Global and the town hall that took
place today. But before heading to Milan on Wednesday night, I had some cat=
ching up to do with people in London, and missed today=E2=80=99s Gucci show=
=2E It was business as usual, I was tol=
d, with the requisite <em>White</em> <=
em>Lotus</em> stars (<strong>Parker Posey</strong> is finally getting her d=
ue), a live orchestra playing a score composed by <strong>Justin Hurwitz</s=
trong> (of <em>Whiplash </em>and<em> La La Land </em>fame), and a collectio=
n that the press release gods called =E2=80=9Cfoundational.=E2=80=9D
Interesting that they used dark Gucci green for the catwalk rather than for=
mer designer <strong>Sabato De Sarno</strong>=E2=80=99s Ancora red. The col=
lection itself was as interstitial as can be: a very <strong>Jackie Kennedy=
</strong>=E2=80=93wearing=E2=80=93Gucci moment. Now, we wait.=C2=A0</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-=
bottom:0px;">Otherwise, it=E2=80=99s been good to be in London for a minute=
=2E I made it to The Dover (yet<em> ano=
ther</em> Italian-leaning, wood-panele=
d
establishment, this time from the former C.O.O. of Soho House) and Dover St=
reet Market (mostly for the Phoebe Philo installation). I also stopped by t=
he new Ala=C3=AFa store=E2=80=94love a bookshop-in-shop. However, my most c=
onsequential shopping-related experience was walking out of the Oxford Circ=
us tube station to buy kids=E2=80=99 clothes at Arket. <br/><br/>My first j=
ob ever<em> and </em>my last job before Puck had offices on Great Titchfiel=
d Street, so I=E2=80=99ve been exiting that station on a fairly regular bas=
is for
more than 20 years. Until 2021, I was greeted by a block-long Topshop, wher=
e I once spent a good deal of my disposable income on acrylic jewelry, poin=
ty flats, and going-out tops. In the city where high-low dressing was inven=
ted, Topshop brought <em>everyone</em> together. Now, it will soon house an=
 Ikea, the long-term lease purchased by the Swedish furniture company for j=
ust =C2=A3378 million from a bankrupt Arcadia Group after retail mogul <str=
ong>Sir Philip Green</strong>=E2=80=99s cancellation. (Topshop
paid something like =C2=A3500 million for the same lease.) <br/><br/>Anyway=
, it was a shock to my system, and sort of underscores the global retail cr=
isis. London remains a great shopping city=E2=80=94with interesting develop=
ment in tonier areas like Sloane Square and Marylebone=E2=80=94but that che=
ap-chic high-street fix is mostly found online these days. That=E2=80=99s w=
hy Sarah=E2=80=99s item today on ShopMy entering the U.K. market is so pres=
